🔧 LEVEL 3: Engineering (Reactor Diagnostics)
Technical Analysis tells you WHEN to enter a trade. Fundamental Analysis tells you WHAT to buy. The world's greatest wealth builders — Buffett, Lynch, Munger — built their fortunes by deeply understanding the businesses behind the tickers. Check the engine room before you purchase the ship.

3.1 Hull Integrity (Reading Financial Statements)
Every listed company files three core documents quarterly and annually. These tell the complete story of the business.

The Income Statement (Profit and Loss):
Revenue (Top Line): Total credits earned from selling products or services. Growing revenue is the first green flag.
Gross Profit = Revenue minus Cost of Goods Sold. Shows production efficiency.
EBITDA: Earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortization. The raw operational engine output.
Net Profit (Bottom Line): What's left after everything. This is what you care about.
Net Profit Margin: Net Profit divided by Revenue. A 20% margin means ₹20 of pure profit per ₹100 sold.
🚨 Red Flag: Revenue growing but profit margin shrinking. Costs are rising faster than sales.

The Balance Sheet:
A snapshot of what the company OWNS vs what it OWES on a single day.
Assets: Cash, inventory, equipment, intellectual property.
Liabilities: All outstanding loans, payables, and obligations.
Shareholder Equity = Total Assets minus Total Liabilities. This is the net value belonging to you as an owner.
Growing equity year-over-year means the ship is being upgraded.

The Cash Flow Statement (The Ultimate Truth):
Net Profit can be engineered through accounting tricks. Cash cannot be faked.
Operating Cash Flow (OCF): Cash generated purely from the core business. Must be positive and growing.
Free Cash Flow (FCF) = Operating Cash Flow minus Capital Expenditure. The purest wealth-generation metric.
Strong FCF allows a company to pay dividends, buy back shares, and fund growth without new debt.
🚨 Rule: Never invest in a company showing negative OCF for more than 2 consecutive years.

3.2 Efficiency Ratios (Valuation Scanners)
P/E Ratio (Price-to-Earnings): Current Share Price divided by Earnings Per Share.
Interpretation: How many Rupees are you paying for ₹1 of annual earnings?
P/E of 30 = You're paying ₹30 for ₹1 of profit. A 30-year payback at current earnings.
Always compare P/E within the same industry. A P/E of 20 can be cheap for pharma and expensive for banking.

P/B Ratio (Price-to-Book): Market Price divided by Net Asset Value per Share.
P/B below 1: You're buying the ship for less than its liquidation value. Deep value territory — investigate why.

ROE (Return on Equity): Net Profit divided by Shareholder Equity.
ROE above 15% generally means management is efficiently compounding your capital.
Warning: High ROE driven entirely by heavy debt is a trap. Cross-check the Debt-to-Equity ratio.

Debt-to-Equity Ratio: Total Debt divided by Shareholder Equity.
Below 0.5: Conservatively built. Low financial risk.
Above 1.0: Heavily leveraged. Dangerous during economic slowdowns.
Exception: Banking companies operate with structurally high D/E — don't penalize them for it.

3.3 Cargo Harvest (Corporate Actions)
Dividends: Cash profit distributions to shareholders.
Dividend Yield = Annual Dividend per Share divided by Current Price. Typical range: 1% to 4%.
🚨 Dividend Trap: Very high yield (above 8%) often means the share price has crashed, inflating the yield. Investigate before buying.

Stock Splits and Bonus Shares: More shares are issued, price adjusts proportionally. Total value unchanged. Improves liquidity.

Buybacks: Company purchases its own shares, reducing total count. EPS rises automatically even if profits are flat.
This is one of the most bullish signals management can send — it means they believe the stock is undervalued.

3.4 Core Design (Economic Moats)
Warren Buffett's Principle: "What we're trying to do is find a business with a wide and long-lasting moat — protecting a terrific economic castle."
A moat is a sustainable competitive advantage that prevents rivals from eating your profits.

Brand Power: Customers pay premium for the name alone. Apple. Coca-Cola. Titan.
Network Effects: The product becomes more valuable as more people use it. WhatsApp. LinkedIn. Stock exchanges themselves.
High Switching Costs: Replacing the product is so painful, customers stay forever. Oracle databases. Tally accounting software.
Cost Advantages: Produce at structurally lower cost than all competitors due to scale or proprietary process.
Regulatory Moats: Government-issued licenses that block new entrants. Airport operators. Telecom spectrum holders. Power distribution utilities.

